  {
    "type": "message",
    "text": "<@UA14TGLTC> I feel liveness/tangibility is important not just for comprehension but also things like immediate verification of ideas, easy exploration, accidental discovery etc. I agree that good thought patterns (mental models?) are useful as well, but wont a live visualization help greatly with *forming* good patterns (specially if the visualizations are well designed)? \n\nIn the end I think mental simulation is just not scalable in a way that tangible, live visualization is. The debate between mental/internal and visual/external forms kind of seems like the old debate against writing via Socrates - the argument being that learning writing would 'introduce forgetfulness'. I believe even people with very strong mental capacity will benefit if they can use a more powerful external medium to help them.",
    "user": "U8A5MS6R1",
